==Old English==

===Alternative spellings===
Nyd, nied, ned, neod

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*nauda-'', from Indo-European ''*nau-, *nū-'' ‘death, corpse’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[ned|nēd]], Old Saxon [[nod|nōd]] (Dutch [[nood]]), Old High German [[not|nōt]] (German [[Not]] ‘need, hardship, emergency’), Old Norse [[nauð]] (Swedish [[nöd]]), Gothic [[𐌽𐌰𐌿𐌸𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Lithuanian [[novyti|nõvyti]] ‘oppress, destroy’, Old Church Slavonic [[уныти]] (Russian [[ныть]] ‘throbbing pain’).

